< review>
Found it indiscrete and impersonal.

I had questions that I wanted answered but there was no brochure so had to ask at the front desk in front of everyone.  The room was the size of a walk-in wardrobe and had 10 chairs with people queing to see the doctor - sat there staring at their phones.

I was directed to the website and made to feel stupid.  I was told to fill out a disclaimer form, prove my ID and pay $75 or $95 before I had any idea what this money was actually buying.  It was not clear what was expected from the moment I walked in to the moment I walked out 5 mins later feeling like a fool.

When I go into a doctors practice I expect to see posters on the walls, magazines in the rack and brochures explaining stuff. Certainly, front of desk staff need to know how to handle people politely before thrusting impersonal disclaimers in their hands and announcing pricing to ever√Ωone jammed in the closet.

None of this was present, making the whole experience feel dodgy. Hence why I made a sharp exit.< /review>

Given the circumstances of the pandemic, clients are currently unable to accompany their pets inside the clinic for appointments. This action is taken to protect the health of clients and clinic staff. I greatly appreciate the concern demonstrated by the staff of Oak Grove Animal Hospital.

In lieu of client physical presence, the examining doctor places a call to the client at the conclusion of the appointment, explains the results of the exam or treatment, offers any suggestions they may have for the health maintenance of the animal, and answers any questions raised by the client.

This is truly a most professional and caring staff across the board. I cannot recommend their clinic to persons and pets requiring veterinary services.<//text>

< review>
Dr. Thies has been my dog's vet for two years, since we moved to the area. He has given her all of her vaccinations in the past two years. This time, after I told him at length about how in her old age she has been nipping at some people and asking whether she should be medicated for anxiety, and after he palpated all her legs, belly, and head and had used his stethoscope and examined her eyes, he went to give her the bordatella vaccine by mouth and she got startled/afraid and nipped at him. Then as he proceeded to upbraid me and blame me and refuse further treatment to her, she stood there completely calmly. I don't know if she actually hurt him in any way, but I certainly saw no signs of blood. It's not like she's a bloodthirsty attack dog. He told me I should have warned him (wasn't I just telling all about how she'd been nipping people?) and that I should have muzzled her (he's been her vet for two years and never told me that before, but now I somehow should have known that and it was completely unforgivable that I didn't?). Anyway, his exact words were "You are dismissed," before declaring that I should have warned or told him and that I should have muzzled her. His vet tech told me when I was trying to pay in confusion and tears that they have muzzles there. Why didn't he muzzle her and continue vaccinating her? How can a vet not expect that an animal, especially a geriatric dog who he's just been told had nipped some people, might react in fear to having their mouth grabbed? It makes no sense that an experienced vet would be unable to deal with this. You get the sense that this guy has academic knowledge but is ill suited to work with the public or any animal that is not at all times completely submissive to all humans. He should be a lab researcher, not a veterinarian.< /review>

< review>
The location is so Tucked away, kind of  hidden way down on the Peninsulaüèñ. It almost feels exclusive.  However, they do let anyone in LOL. You will find couples dressed up that arrived in theirü§© Lambo or the group of guys that just got done fishing, or me who rolls up on a beach cruiser in flip flops from a long hard day of doing nothing üí™üèº.

The staff is wonderful they have the same people as before Covid.  I‚Äôm so happy they were able to make it through.  They do pretty good take out to which I find is very difficult for most sushi restaurants of their caliber.

The Uni is to die for I won‚Äôt have it anywhere else ask for the Uni martini with truffle Yum to the maximumüëÖüí¶.

I go between the OMAKASE and then just ordering my favorites. A surprise dish that is my favorite is a simple little 3.50 homemade tofu... I like it so much sometimes when I order to go I get two of them!!!

<rate>5</rate><Gmap_id>0x80dce06b6e54a64b:0xabbea056a05e2359</Gmap_id><review>A quaint sushi ‚Äúbar‚Äù in Newport. They are very welcoming as all the staff greet you as you walk in. <user>102576439372137525356< /user>< Name>

< Date>

<Rating>5<//Rating>< text>
Went to nana san but the wait was too long so we decided to try this place and I am so glad that we did. Must order: agedashi tofu (this blew me away and it was only $3.50), bluefin tuna sushi (I've never had amazing tuna outside of Japan so this was a first), yellowtail sushi, salmon/salmon belly sushi, freshwater eel (same as what you get at any sushi restaurant but I love this so I'll put it here anyway), striped jack (mackerel family), soft shell crab roll and of course, fatty tuna sushi. I tried a bunch of other sushi/rolls (crunchy roll, golden eye snapper, etc.) but these are the ones I would order when I go back. Also, a tip: be friendly with the sushi chef as they tell you if you need to put soysauce or not on your sushi and I feel that it enhances the dining experience. I will definitely come back when I have a other special occasion.< /text>

<name>Walter Tran< /name><response>{'time': 1574711910469, 'text': 'Thank you so much for coming to San Shi Go Newport Beach, Please come again anytime!! by the way , we are going to have Sushi Omakase 101from 12/2(Mon)~12/5(Thur) 7 dishes course including dessert for $65.We are happy to take a reservation. Please call us afer 4:30pm otherwise please leave a call back number and your name.We are looking forward to having you.'}< /response>< review>
This is THEE place to get amazing Sushi. I've had Omakase from many other great places like Oshima, Nana San, Shunka, Nobu Malibu, and Go's Mart, but I have to say that San Shi Go is my favorite. I've been here 3 times and my experience here has only gotten better every time.

TLDR: Hidden gem, fantastic food, amazing staff & chef, ask for Hiro, take the ferry!

I love that it still feels like a hidden gem, so you don't have to worry about waiting. Granted that the times I've been have been during the weekday...

First, the ambiance is nothing that wows you, it's a typical sushi restaurant with a bar that seats around 15 people or so, and a few more tables on the side to hold more. But for me, I don't come here for the ambiance, nor do I care to pay for it, if I did, I can go to Nobu.

The food is amazing, the chefs taking their time to prepare and plate each dish delicately. Each chef plates/prepares their dishes differently from one another, they just share the same seasonal ingredients that they get. They genuinely care about serving you the best food they have to offer.

Aside from normal Japanese sushi fair, they have 2 Omakase menues, raw fish or cooked items. You can't go wrong with either one, just depends on what you're in the mood for. This isn't to say that after your Omakase meal, you can't make special requests.

By far the reason why this places beats out the rest, is the atmosphere & rapport that the staff & chefs build with you. I've been here 3 times, and every time has been with my man Hiro! He's a great guy that is humble, funny, and the most amazing Chef ever! He straight up fed my GF sushi with his hands, so I think that makes us family now?

Not to say that you don't get to meet other people, we've talked to the owner Daiske (hope I spelled that right) quite a few times, and loved all the stories that he's told us about from his previous jobs and about all the other Sushi chefs that he's friends with and known for 15+ years.

If you've actually read through this long review and plan on going, here is my tip, straight from Daiske's mouth!!

Sit at the sushi bar, and eat the sushi with your hands (it's a fun experience!). At the beginning, you're given a towelette, don't let them take it away, keep it around to use after each sushi round. Daiske explained to us that eating with your hands enables you to put the entire sushi in your mouth to enjoy all in 1 bite, so you allow all ingredients to harmonize in your mouth. They don't consider it rude to eat with your hands, instead they actually respect you more, because you actually know how to enjoy sushi. And that they don't usually tell customers because they don't want to disrespect any of their customers, but feels they do a disservice to their customers if they don't let them in on this little cultural secret.

They've said that once the sushi has been prepared for every second you don't eat it, the sushi changes, the rice can fall apart, and the temperature of the rice alters the taste of the fish. You can believe me or not, but it's fun and offers a different experience.<//review>

Went here for lunch and the crowds were not too bad alot of sushi restaurants have a ton of yuppies going in and out of it. The food was great and the non sushi japanese food was excellent. <rating>2< /rating><Text>We had the Omakase dinner and came in very hungry. We didn't like the sweet live shrimp moving all around on our plate & it caused 2 of us to just stop eating altogether. <username>Michael Wisniewski</username>< Time>
1448950278376<//Time>
<rating>4< /rating><Text>I cannot give San Shi Go 5 stars simply because of the speed of the service. The omakase quality was excellent in my opinion -- a little on the expensive side.  I did my best to enjoy the experience, and I cannot fault them for the type of crowd they attract -- typical Newport -- mixture of tourist, the rich, those on dates, adventurers, the whole gamut. Going into a restaurant such as this in a tourist location , I did have some preconceptions about the place that it would be an atypical sushi experience.

My GF and I ordered both order Omakase which was great... however each course took anywhere from 1 minute to 10 minutes. It's not a structured experience if that's what you want. Our chef was extremely funny and full of energy and I think that is what the allure and charm of this restuarant is at the sushi bar.

If you are looking for quiet experience where you will be served in a traditional sense then find sushi elsewhere in Orange County. But if you are looking for an interactive experience with the Chef, you have patience, and you genuinely want to be an engaged participant in your meal then this is a place for you.</Text>< Pictures>
None<//Pictures>

114383741689319887690< /userid>
< name>
Kim L (cheerstofood)</name>
<time>1413845583053</time><Rate>4<//Rate>< text>
Omakase (regular w/ Appetizers & Sashimi / Sushi) Review:
Omakase here is way too strict with rules; if you order Omakase at your table then everyone has to order the same one no exceptions.
Agedashi Tofu w/ corn: 2.5 stars
Very subtle hint of ginger & corn. This would have tasted better with white corn pureed instead of of just having yellow corn mixed in with the tofu.
Yellow Tail w/ Tuna martini w/ Ponzu Sauce: 4 stars
Very fresh but the slices of onion & tomatoes threw me off a bit.
Halibut Sashimi w/ drop of Ginger & Sweet Plum: 2 stars
Very light tasting with dash of halibut w/ citrus; this was way too warm, would have been better chilled.
Sweet Live Shrimp: 5 stars
Antennas on the shrimp head was still wiggling around when the plate was brought to me. This plate is not for the faint of heart =) This was one of the freshest sweet shrimps which Ive had. =)
Sea-bass Chilean: 2 stars
Had a weird sour taste to it that I didn't not care for. =( This is one of my fave fishes but this was just weird tasting.
Albacore roll: 4 stars
Loved the sweet rice paper that had sprinkles of black sesame in grained in it. Great balance of flavors here but had a big portion of rice here.
House special soy sauce, infused w/ Sake: 4.5 stars
Very tasty & enhanced the Sashimi dishes even more.
Service: Very slow & forgot to bring out some of the other dishes which we ordered. He even forgot to let us know that our Omakase course was over. -1 Star
It was my GF's Bday & they didnt even offer a complementary dessert for her. Boo. =(
Ambiance: B+
Small cozy Japanese restaurant which the bar area dominates most of the area.
Parking is a big pain here so plan ahead some extra time to find parking. =(<//text>

< review>
We encountered a blatant SCAM when we came in to purchase a used car advertised for $5,995 online.

I ran the CARFAX report, it was clean, and had my mechanic meet me there. He checked it out thoroughly and gave it clean bill of health. $250 but I knew that and it's worth it to me.

We sat down to get the total dollar amount and they informed me there was a non-optional Dealer Accessory for StarGard security system that would cost $1,500. I told them I didn't want it. They said it was mandatory.

Went round and round with 3 people there and their best final offer was to reduce the unwanted accessory to $1,000. We had spent our entire morning and $250 to my mechanic without them disclosing this up front. Their lawyers have small print at the bottom of the website that prices don't include taxes, etc, and Dealer Accessories.

Incredible. The senior manager told me they low-balled the price but need to make money somewhere to stay in business. OK, so advertise up front that the $5,995 price doesn't include the $1,500 non-optional StarGard system. This is flat out misrepresentation, plain and simple.

They refused to even admit how underhanded this is. Even if the car was worth $7,000, I wouldn't have agreed to it at this point because of the way they constructed this deal. Really low life technique in my opinion. Be up-front. No reasonable person would expect that a car advertised for $5,995 would actually cost them $7,000-$7,500 before tax, title and license.< /review>

<rate>1< /rate><Review>I wish I can say good things about this dealership.

We arrived at this dealership the weekend before July 4.  They were already advertising July 4 holiday offers.  We were in the market to purchase a 2019 FWD RDX Tech Package.

Another dealership quoted me a discount price for a 2019 FWD RDX Tech Package, which was about 12% of the MSRP value.  I consulted with Acura of Alhambra's staff via telephone a day or two before, specifically their Product Specialist, Ivan Contreras, to see if they would beat the price the other dealership offered.

During my conversations with Ivan over the phone, I was unambiguous and unequivocal that I was looking to purchase a vehicle with a certain down payment with the intention to finance the remaining balance.  I further advised that we had financing through our bank, but would entertain financing through Acura Financial if any additional incentives made sense.  Lastly, I told Ivan that we were absolutely buying a car this weekend, but that with work, the kid's ballet and karate, I did not have a lot of time to negotiate back and forth.  I explicitly told Ivan, "I don't want to waste my time," and that if he can beat the quoted discount, I will drive over and buy from them.

Ivan asked me to forward the other dealership's quote to him for his and his manager's review to determine whether they can do a better deal.
Later that day, Ivan called me via phone and advised that his manager would match the price, and that he would offer a $50.00 discount just to incentive us to buy from Acura of Alhambra.  Because I was at lunch during our telephone conversation, I asked that Ivan email me the details of their offer.

However, Ivan advised that he was not allowed to put anything in writing via email, which should have automatically been a red flag.

Nonetheless, I confirmed again verbally via telephone that we were looking for a purchase, not a lease.  I scheduled an appointment to meet with Ivan the next day.

Upon arrival, Ivan was not available at our scheduled appointment.  Another individual helped us.  Once we started talking about the figures, they would not honor the approximate 12% discount off MSRP that Ivan had offered to me.  They explained that the offer made to me was in contemplation of a lease price.  This was despite me having been absolutely clear and unequivocal that we were only interested in a purchase of a vehicle and not a lease.  They absolutely would not honor the price previously negotiated; their best price for purchase did not even come close; their offer was at about 9% off the MSRP.

Eventually, Ivan made himself available to explain his deceit.  Ivan said that there was a "miscommunication" between the parties, explaining that he thought we were talking lease numbers.  He was implying that I did not listen to him carefully enough during our telephone conversation.

At this point in time, it became entirely clear to me why he previously refused to memorialize our telephonic price negotiations in writing via email the day before.  His intentions were to promise me a price to lure me to walk into the dealership, then renege on the price as negotiated as soon as I appear.

I want to note that the staff was nice and accommodating upon our arrival.  However, they became extremely deceptive once the price was brought up.

We eventually purchased a brand new 2019 FWD RDX Tech Package later that night at another dealership.  The dealership we purchased from not only matched the 12% off MSRP discount, they gave us an even better discount at approximately 13.5% off MSRP.

I compared some of the discounts from other dealers in Southern California for this model.  In fact, Alhambra of Acura was offered one of the lowest discounts, even with a holiday event.

I noticed that the most competitive discounts were from Acura dealerships in Orange, Riverside, and San Bernardino.  We ultimately purchased from a dealership in Riverside County.

I hope this cautionary review helps steer unwitting buyers from Alhambra's deceitful and predatory business dealings.<//Review>< Pictures>

< Review>
Cozy and contemporary diner feel to this spot!

Besides the carafe size that was disappointing for 3 people, the food was delicious and service was great!

Scrambled eggs and biscuits was comfort to the soul. Buttermilk chicken is a must get!  Their fried batter was so bomb, lightly crisp and treasurable to the taste buds. The brunch menu for Restaurant Week is a solid deal, 1 donut + coffee or tea (jade green was some really good green tea!), 1 cocktail, and 1 main entree (came in huge portion).
We tried the fried chicken with biscuit and pork sausage gravy (awesome fried chicken, crispy, juicy and flavorful) the kimchi fried rice with shoyu egg (4 halves üòÆ)

Tip:

< review>
I came here for my 30th birthday during Restaurant Week and the team at Hopscotch was very accommodating leading up to dinner - very responsive over email, answering questions, giving me an option to add a customizable message on the menu, etc.

I didn‚Äôt have a cocktail but my friends did and they all enjoyed them. The Norte√±o comes to mind as a particularly good one with green pepper vodka (perhaps from St. George‚Äôs?). Nice selection of wine that is reasonably priced. As for the food, Restaurant Week for our group size was a set menu, family style.

A few key items: started off with a kale salad (üëçüèΩ), Kakiage - tempura veggie/bamboo shoots which was great, and burrata with squash (best of the bunch).

For the mains, the spatzel with brats was fine but nothing unique about it. Same with the buttermilk fried chicken which seems to be their most popular dish (not as much flavor as expected and ours were a bit dried out). The soba malfadine carbonara was great! I added some salt to bring out the flavors after breaking the yolk but I liked the fusion between Japanese + Italian.

Dessert was awesome. Loved the donut and mud pie combo. Donut could‚Äôve been hotter but I imagine it‚Äôs because of our large party + the extra 45 seconds of the HBD song üòÜ

Overall, I didn‚Äôt think it was worth the $40 price tag, mostly because the quantities weren‚Äôt on par. Now, this might be due to the group/family style/restaurant week factor but none of us left full. One note about their service: they graciously comped one meal as my gluten-free guest was mostly neglected throughout the meal. I had to ask several times what she could eat and what she couldn‚Äôt eat despite stating in advance and getting confirmation days before) her dietary restrictions. That bit was disappointing but this stuff happens and I appreciated their manager apologizing profusely and making amends. Would I return? Possibly but perhaps with a smaller group.<//review>

<rating>5< /rating><Date>1589334418564< /Date><user_name>Evelyn Lindsey< /user_name>< review>
Ate there alone the first time (around 3pm - because awesomely they do not close between lunch and dinner!) I wish I had a video of the experience because it was just SO sweet. But first and foremost let me tell you the meal was scrumptious. Eggs Benedict salmon style: Perfect poached eggs with very yummy hollandaise on thick fresh lovely egg bread - a hunk of smoked salmon - juicy and house made - and the best brunch potatoes I ever ate - made in their own little individual caste iron pan. Delish green salad or fruit salad also part of the game. The server was a guy so kind so thoughtful and professional it brought out my Cheshire Cat smile! I‚Äôve now gone several times with family and friends and Hopscotch has that kind of discipline and consistency I really do love. Bartender is also a sweetheart. I do happen to like their red leather bistro diner look. I‚Äôm the spoiled one so trust me. Top notch effort and cuisine. Go uptown for this one!</review>

< Review>
Hands down the best restaurant in Oakland.  Their pork chop is my favorite thing to eat when it is on the menu.  Last time I had braised Lamb neck which sounds a little adventurous, but blew everyone in the group away.  Wine list and service are on point too.  Fried chicken is awesome, but I feel like there are too many other good items on the menu to warrant ordering it unless you are in a big group.  Should be everyone's go to restaurant recommendation if anyone asks because they are always consistent and won't let you down.<//Review>

<rate>4</rate><text>Hopscotch is a tastefully laid out American Japanese fusion food affaire. Small restaurant with seating for maybe 30 inside, a few tables outside.

Our food was pretty stellar. Fried chicken, biscuits and gravy, country potatoes, all great. Drinks were good as well (gin fizz). We did have to wait over 30 minutes for our order to be retaken because our bartender forgot to put it in, so I have to detract a star for that; realistically, I don't see service being an issue at all normally.

Also a great selection of unique scotches which I can't wait to try next time. Be aware the prices are not cheap but the food portions are pretty generous. This place is worth a try, you won't regret it.</text>< user_name>
Nate G.</user_name>

<Text>Excellent food and service. This is a bit of a hole-in-the-wall with four tables outside and maybe ten inside. You can also eat at the bar. Their mixed drinks are excellent and unusual. Our shared starter of tempura-fried vegetables was very tasty, but a bit on the greasy side. Two of us had the buttermilk fried chicken and one the halibut. All the mains were great. We shared one dessert, the doughnuts. Don't be put off by the name. Try it. Overall I would give Hopscotch five stars except I think it is overpriced. Three of us with drinks, a bottle of wine, one starter, one dessert and three mains racked up a bill of $270 with tip. That is very expensive for what and where it is.<//Text>< UserId.>

< Review>
Cute little place for some simple but good food. The food portion of the menu is small - 5 or 6 entrees and another 5 or 6 appetizers. The wine selection is quite big and the prices are pretty reasonable. They also have 4 or 5 draft beers to choose from. The food is good quality and done with care and creativity. There is bit of Japanese/Asian influence but overall result is very good. The service is very good. The staff is courteous and attentive without being intrusive. This will be my go-to place if I am in the Oakland area.< /Review>

< Review>
We had the fried chicken with gravy, the donuts, and the hopscotch burger. The fried chicken was phenomenal, one of the best I've had in the East bay. The burger was tender and juicy, and I'd say on the top 5 burgers I've had though perhaps a little too drippy. The donuts were small portion for the price but they include a delicious butterscotch cream that is really good. Brunch is definitely the best time to go but seating is limited so be prepared to wait.</Review>

<Review>If you find yourself in Oakland, unsure about where to get food,go to Hopscotch. This place will make your food dreams come true. I ordered the Lotus fritters (delicious) as my starter, and the Pork chop‚Äé (amazing) as my main course. Those were the two best choices I had made in a while. The fritters were perfect. <text>I love this kind of upscale Japanese-American fusion food. I haven't seen that much Japanese-American fusion, so I thought that this place was pretty cool and unique. I really enjoyed the food here and the interesting flavors that come from combining Japanese cuisine with American cuisine. I came here for the brunch and got the Braised Pork Belly Benedict. It was very nontraditional and different from a regular eggs benedict. The pork belly had a soy sauce asian flavor which was very interesting in combination with the hollandaise. It was also very tender and fatty which added more richness to the dish. The dish as a whole was almost too rich and I'm glad it came with a side salad.</text>< time>

<Name>Dickie Henshall< /Name>< Date>
1561355900286< /Date>
<rating>5< /rating>< Text>
We ordered the uni ravioli, the asparagus, and the fried chicken. The uni ravioli is a magic trick invented to allow you to imagine a sashimi scallop wrapped around uni is a ravioli, supported by shoshito oil and herbs. OMG. The asparagus, perfectly firm without any woodiness, had a lovely mayo sauce, flakes of parmesan, and the platonic ideal of anchovy slivers (silver skin, a gentle salty smoky flavor). The buttermilk fried chicken was slightly hot, and a confusing anatomy of white meat (even on the drumstick) and wonderfully crunchy crust. A house-made chili sauce, thin, clear, hot and still with flavor, was provide in a cruet. You must get yourself here.</Text>

That cannot be a true chef creating that menu. Cod is a soft fish great for stews or battering. They served it with cooked spinach and miso. It was an extremely mushy dish. No texture. The fried chicken came in a bed of cabbage. It was fried hard and had thin and dry batter. The sunchokes were tasty, but needed an aioli or some type of Sauce. The chicken could use some dipping sauce also. They served cold mozzarella on top of cooked veggies. And gave us tiny, cold, uncooked tofu cubes with what tasted like the sweet red sauce you get from the Chinese restaurant. Absolutely nothing about anything on that menu was worth our $150 meal. Fortunately the company paid for it, but we could've went ANYWHERE cheaper and had quality options. The idea is high end, but the food is not.</Text>< pictures>
None</pictures>

< Review>
If there's a better place for brunch in Oakland, I don't know what it is. I can't seem to stop coming here. The bartenders - Aubrey and Cody - make excellent cocktails. < Review>
I will drive across town (when I could be sleeping in) to ensure I get a table for brunch at Hopscotch. Or, I could simply make a reservation. It's worth it. Everything we've had here is worthwhile. First base burger,  fried chicken, hash, tonkatsu sandwich... for me, the standout is the kimchee fried rice with pork belly and jidoku eggs. Servers are quick and friendly; bartender is amazingly talented and just the right amount of chatty, ingredients are stellar and it all adds up to the pot o' gold experience. Post-brunch satisfaction has reached its zenith, thanks to Hopscotch.</Review>

<Review>The staff was attentive, friendly and worked well as a team. I wish the food worked well. Our party was 3 and not one of us gave the food high marks.

The uni in the Yonsei Oysters were undetectable. The oyster and salmon roe overpowered the Uni.

I couldn't taste the tongue in the 1st Base Burger. Luckily it was served cut in half and I picked out the tongue to eat it plain.

Happy hour beer was served in smaller glasses, so not a real happy hour price.

I did enjoy the desserts: Mochi Cake and Butterscotch Pudding.

I had high hopes as the ingredients were intriguing. I probably won't be going back as my try list for the Bay Area is pretty long, but I would give it a try again if someone asked me to go - only because the staff was great and the menu looked great. The food wasn't bad, just didn't the high price.<//Review><pics>None</pics>< response>

< Review>
It's wonderful to dine in a restaurant where there are no strangers. In Hopscotch, a less than 40 seat bistro meets diner mid-priced Japanese‚Äëinspired restaurant in "Uptown Oakland", no one is a stranger. It's steps aways from the Fox Theater and, with a few more steps, the Paramount Theater. A new "stranger" is greeted by Jenny and feed by Kyle (co-owners) only to be most welcomed by Jason the mixologist behind the oversized blue white marbled counter. And there was no "bottom two" ingredients deleted from his complex cocktails. Of which are enough to fill several menus; check it out: our two menus didn't match when it came to the cocktail list. And that kind of says it about Hopscotch. Worth checking out.</Review>

<Pics>None</Pics>< Text>
A charming quaint local Oakland spot with wonderful food.  We sat at the bar and ordered what the bartender recommended which included beer steamed clams, kanpachi sashimi, and the duck liver pate and opted for the fried chicken for dinner.  All were quite good and wonderfully prepared.  The service was attentive and good.  The decor is that of a friendly neighborhood bistro.  I called a half an hour before we arrived asking if there was availability at the bar.  We had to wait about five minutes when we got there but then a spot cleared up for us.  It's nice that they have a few chairs outside and it's a pleasant place to wait and take in the city on a warm night.

We will definitely be back.</Text>

< UserId.>
112172538393316473174</UserId.>
<name>Jace Proctor</name><Date>1417714536157<//Date>< Rate>
3</Rate>
< review>
Hopscotch can be a very conflicting experience.  Brunch is great; dinner is lackluster.  Service is great; then it sucks.  One dish can be amazing; the next dish can be a dud.  I've been here a few times, and always leave scratching my head, wondering how I should feel.  Here are some takeaways:

First of all, the place is TINY.  I think maybe eight tables and a bar with eight stools.  It can be very crowded, so factor that into your plans.

Brunch is very solid.  The fried chicken is out of this world, maybe the best I've had in California.  The Bloody Mary is fantastic.  They'll even do a solid French 75, which isn't always the best experience if the bartender doesn't know their stuff.  If you sit at the bar, the bartenders are always pleasant and your service (and your cocktails) will be great.  Get the donuts, you won't regret it.

A few days ago we went in for a Christmas special "whole lamb platter," which consisted of a few different cuts of lamb, broccoli romanesco, cauliflower puree, and cornbread.  It sounded good in the e-mail, but the dinner was just... underwhelming.  For $65 we got a "portion for two" that was generously made for one, and immediately regretted not ordering something else.  All of the food was fine, but none of it was special.

The service was also pretty bad.  When we asked for cocktail pairings instead of wine pairings, the waitress basically said, "Um, well, the wine is really good. Are you sure you don't want wine?" and then offered no help when it came to cocktails.  In a place that actually has a great bar, you'd think they would be more willing to talk cocktails.  We felt like we were being pushed hard towards the wine pairings in a gross, upselly-type way, and it was a bummer.

I keep thinking I should go back to Hopscotch and give them another try, because for every negative point, there's a positive point.  Really and truly, I've had some great bites and drinks here.  But it's just not solid enough to stay in my thoughts or stomach for long, especially with so many great restaurants in the Oakland/Berkeley area.

Hopscotch needs to up its game.  There are some ballers around here.<//review>

<date>1405457695219< /date><rate>4</rate>< Text>
My partner and I started with the Yonsei Oyster and the fries. The oyster came with uni, salmon roe, and citrus soy. I didn‚Äôt taste a citrus element, the soy was light like a dashi, but it was surprisingly really good in a decadent way and it felt refreshing in the Oakland heat. If I had known how delicious they were, I would have ordered a dozen of these!

The fries were crispy and it came with a Frenso chili aioli that was creamy, a touch spicy, and it‚Äôs something every fatty like me would enjoy.

I ordered the First Base Burger and it came with a house ground chuck, griddled beef tongue, pickled onions, and sesame aioli with a side of Kennebec chips. You can also add bacon or cheddar and I opted for the latter. It‚Äôs not a homerun, but still exciting in its own way. I asked for medium rare and received a rare patty but I found it to tender and juicy. The aioli was sparse so I can‚Äôt tell you what it tasted like, but the pickled onion added a nice contrast to the beef and the sweet bun.

My partner ordered the chicken club and it came with lettuce, cabbage, bacon, tomato, and fried chicken. It was simple but the fried chicken took it up a notch. I only had a bite but have to get it the next time we visit.

Items do not appear as described but we had a good meal here.</Text>

<Review>Came here with a friend for brunch on a Sunday morning around 10:45. Since it was still early, we were seated right away, outside on the patio per our request. Service was wonderful and quick, and they made some nice suggestions for brunch, although their menu is really limited and very much Asian-inspired.

We started our meal with a carafe of Mimosas for $15, which equates to about 1.5 drinks per person. My friend had the kimchi fried rice with miso marinated jidori eggs. We hadn't expected her rice to be so moist and wet, more on the side of risotto than fried rice, though still good. I had the pork belly eggs benedict, which came with a side salad and skillet potatoes. The Benedict was good, though really rich with the creaminess of the egg yolk, hollandaise sauce, and pork belly fat. The side frisee salad had a nice tart vinegrette. The skillet potatoes came out pipping hot on a small cast iron skillet, though it was rather creamy and cheesy, more like potatoes au gratin than the skillet homefries I was expecting for brunch. Since the pork belly eggs benedict was already so rich, the potatoes seemed like excess. I wish I had gotten fruit as a side instead to even the meal out!

Street parking was easy to find. We found out afterwards that their is also a second half to the restaurant two doors down, so there's definitely more seating than the main location shows.<//Review><Rate>4<//Rate><resp>None< /resp><Pics>None< /Pics><UserId.>110288469148184652948< /UserId.><username>Denise Dang</username></record>
